You are a Data analyst at Carrefour Kenya and are currently undertaking a project that will inform the marketing department on the most relevant marketing strategies that will result in the highest no. of sales (total price including tax). Your project has been divided into four parts where youll explore a recent marketing dataset by performing various unsupervised learning techniques and later providing recommendations based on your insights.

# mode function
getmode <- function(v) {
   uniqv <- unique(v)
   uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

library(scales)
library(ggplot2)
plotdata <- dataset %>%
  count(Branch) %>%
  mutate(pct = n / sum(n),
         pctlabel = paste0(round(pct*100), "%"))

# plot the bars as percentages, 
# in decending order with bar labels
ggplot(plotdata, 
       aes(x = reorder(Branch, -pct),
           y = pct)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", 
           fill = "indianred3", 
           color = "black") +
  geom_text(aes(label = pctlabel), 
            vjust = -0.25) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent) +
  labs(x = "Branch", 
       y = "Percent", 
       title  = "Customers per Branch")

> The customers for Branch A were 1% higher compared to branch B and C.

Implementing the Solution

Principal Component Analysis

library(Rtsne)
library(Rcpp)

# select the numerical columns exclude the categorical 
df <- dataset[,c(6,8,12,14,16)]
head(df)
##   Unit.price     Tax   cogs gross.income    Total
## 1      74.69 26.1415 522.83      26.1415 548.9715
## 2      15.28  3.8200  76.40       3.8200  80.2200
## 3      46.33 16.2155 324.31      16.2155 340.5255
## 4      58.22 23.2880 465.76      23.2880 489.0480
## 5      86.31 30.2085 604.17      30.2085 634.3785
## 6      85.39 29.8865 597.73      29.8865 627.6165
# pass df to the prcomp()
dataset.pca <- prcomp(df, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
summary(dataset.pca)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2       PC3       PC4       PC5
## Standard deviation     2.1128 0.7321 2.582e-16 1.735e-16 1.036e-16
## Proportion of Variance 0.8928 0.1072 0.000e+00 0.000e+00 0.000e+00
## Cumulative Proportion  0.8928 1.0000 1.000e+00 1.000e+00 1.000e+00

As a result of principal component we have obtained 5 principal components, each which explains percentage of the total variation of the dataset PC1 explains 89% of the total variance, which means that nearly two-thirds of the information in the dataset can be encapsulated by just that one Principal Component. PC2 explains 10% of the variance.

# plot our pca.
library(devtools)

From the graph we see that the variables Unit.price, cogs and gross income contribute to PC1, with higher values in those variables moving the samples to the right on the plot.
